FAMILY attachments have this advantage over all others, that they are not ſubject to ſatiety. Parental fondneſs is augmented by the growth and expanſion of every charm and merit in a child; and as it naturally happens that the parents begin to decline when the children have arrived at their zenith, reverence for their age and gratitude


for their kindneſs, combined with the tender apprehenſion of loſing them, add ſtrength to our former affectionate feelings, and awaken that almoſt divine enthuſiaſm which inſpired Pope's filial prayer:


" Me let the tender office long engage,

" To rock the cradle of declining Age;

" Explore the thought, explain the aſking eye,

" And keep awhile a parent from the ſky!"
